/td>                                </tr>                               </tbody>                              </table>                             </div> </td>                           </tr>                          </tbody>                         </table>                         <table width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" class="galileo-ap-layout-editor" style="min-width: 100%;">                          <tbody>                           <tr>                            <td class=" editor-col OneColumnMobile" width="100%" align="" valign="top" style="background: rgb(255, 255, 255);" bgcolor="rgb(255, 255, 255)">                             <div class="gl-contains-text">                              <table width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">                               <tbody>                                <tr>                                 <td class="editor-text editor-text " align="left" valign="top" style="color: #485763; display: block; font-family: Calibri,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; padding: 10px 20px; text-align: left; word-wrap: break-word;">                                  <div></div>                                  <div class="text-container galileo-ap-content-editor">                                  <div>                                    <div style="text-align: center;" align="center">                                    <span style="color: rgb(76, 76, 76); font-family: Calibri, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;">There are three main ways to search for Halloween-related programming on the platform:</span>                                   </div>                                    <div style="text-align: center;" align="center">                                    <br>                                   </div>                                    <div style="text-align: center;" align="center">                                    <span style="color: rgb(76, 76, 76); font-family: Calibri, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: bold;">Keyword Search</span>                                   </div>                                    <div style="text-align: center;" align="center">                                     <span style="color: rgb(76, 76, 76); font-family: Calibri, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;">Choose the dates you need, then press the “Keyword” button. Enter words like, “ghost, vampire, fright,” making sure to separate each one with a comma. Click the green “Search ShowSeeker” button and the options will appear in the search results box. </span>                                    <span style="color: rgb(76, 76, 76); font-family: Calibri, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: italic;">Tip: Save keyword searches to quickly find any new programs added during the month of October.</span>                                    <span style="color: rgb(76, 76, 76); font-family: Calibri, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>                                    </div>                                    <div style="text-align: center;" align="center">                                    <br>                                   </div>                                    <div style="text-align: center;" align="center">                                    <span style="color: rgb(76, 76, 76); font-family: Calibri, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: bold;">Genre Search</span>                                   </div>                                    <div style="text-align: center;" align="center">                                    <span style="color: rgb(76, 76, 76); font-family: Calibri, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;">Choose the “Genre” button, then select the type of show you want. “Horror,” “Paranormal,” “Fantasy,” and “Science Fiction” are great categories for this time of year. To select multiple genres, use the control key for PCs or the command key for Macs. Click the green “Search ShowSeeker” button and the options will appear in the search results box.&nbsp;</span>                                   </div>                                    <div style="text-align: center;" align="center">                                    <br>                                   </div>                                    <div style="text-align: center;" align="center">                                     <span style="color: rgb(76, 76, 76); font-family: Calibri, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;">To find Halloween movies, press the “Genre” button, select a category, then choose “Movies." </span>                                    <span style="color: rgb(76, 76, 76); font-family: Calibri, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: italic;">Tip: Sort lists by using the filters in the blue bar above the search results. This makes it easier to group shows together and to delete unwanted programs, before moving them into a proposal.</span>                                    </div>                                    <div style="text-align: center;" align="center">                                    <br>                                   </div>                                    <div style="text-align: center;" align="center">                                    <span style="color: rgb(76, 76, 76); font-family: Calibri, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: bold;">Title Search</span>                                   </div>                                    <div style="text-align: center;" align="center">                                     <span style="color: rgb(76, 76, 76); font-family: Calibri, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;">If you know the title of a television program or movie, or just part of the name, choose the “Title” button and enter the information. Once found, left click on the show and move it to the selected title box. Then click the green “Search ShowSeeker” button to see the results.</span>                                    <span style="color: rgb(76, 76, 76); font-family: Calibri, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: italic;"> Tip: You can easily select multiple titles using this function.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>                                    <span style="color: rgb(76, 76, 76); font-family: Calibri, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;">&nbsp;</span>                                    </div>                                   </div>                                 </div> </td>                                </tr>                               </tbody>                              </table>                             </div> </td>                           </tr>                          </tbody>                         </table>                         <table width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" class="galileo-ap-layout-editor" style="min-width: 100%;">                          <tbody>                           <tr>                            <td class=" editor-col OneColumnMobile" width="100%" align="" valign="top" style="background: rgb(255, 255, 255);" bgcolor="rgb(255, 255, 255)">                             <div class="gl-contains-spacer">                              <table class="editor-spacer" width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">                               <tbody>                                <tr>                                 <td class="" align="center" valign="top">                                  <table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">                                   <tbody>                                    <tr>                                     <td class="spacer-base" width="100%" align="center" valign="top" style="height: 1px; line-height: 1px; padding-bottom: 10px;">             